00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:52.240
aspects like these.

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:58.209
These are two fishermen off the coast of Madagascar,
living on one or two dollars a day, 100 percent

00:03:58.209 --> 00:04:00.640
protein for their families is coming from
the sea.

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:06.690
So the sea is not just some fantastic aspect
of biodiversity for us to go to vacation to

00:04:06.690 --> 00:04:11.069
and see, but is an elemental part of coastal
livelihoods throughout the world.

00:04:11.069 --> 00:04:16.639
And this is really an important essence of
the oceans to also remember.

00:04:16.639 --> 00:04:23.189
So when, on the other side of fishing from
the sea, thereís also as we know, and probably

00:04:23.189 --> 00:04:27.509
people have heard far too much about, the
over-fishing crisis that we face on the planet.

00:04:27.509 --> 00:04:31.629
We have trawlers, trawling in very close to
the shore line in places that have almost

00:04:31.629 --> 00:04:37.940
no rules, taking in bycatch of marine turtles
and dolphins and over harvesting too many

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:41.469
species without any sort of regulations.

00:04:41.469 --> 00:04:46.240
We are now importing far more seafood from
the developing world than we produce in the

00:04:46.240 --> 00:04:48.009
developed world.

00:04:48.009 --> 00:04:52.650
We are inadequately managing our fisheries
and taking them from places we have no idea

00:04:52.650 --> 00:04:56.550
with the population structure, how much fish
we could possibly take out of the ocean.

00:04:56.550 --> 00:05:02.569
So thereís a significant challenge that is
the industrial scale fisheries that are increasingly

00:05:02.569 --> 00:05:06.650
moving into resource-poor and governance -poor
places.

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:11.979
An articulation of this is the crisis we face
with shark finning and shark fisheries today.

00:05:11.979 --> 00:05:16.780
We woke up to the whales in the early part
of last century and we started an international

00:05:16.780 --> 00:05:19.360
commitment to saving the great whales on this
planet.

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:22.419
As a result, around the world whale populations
are rebounding.

00:05:22.419 --> 00:05:27.780
In 1970s, we woke up to sea turtles and as
a result many sea turtle populations around

00:05:27.780 --> 00:05:29.259
the world are rebounding.

00:05:29.259 --> 00:05:32.509
Today, weíre waking up to the shark finning
crisis.

00:05:32.509 --> 00:05:39.580
WCS research that we had done in the last
decade indicates that between 40 and 70 million

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:42.819
sharks are taken, a year, from our oceans.

00:05:42.819 --> 00:05:46.909
Almost none of the shark populations are assessed,
almost none of these fisheries are controlled.

00:05:46.909 --> 00:05:51.770
This is a species crisis in the oceans of
our day.

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:57.249
As we, as was articulated two summers ago,
oil and gas extraction and is moving, has

00:05:57.249 --> 00:06:02.080
moved into the Gulf of Mexico and is now moving
off shore to a number of countries around

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:03.080
the world.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:08.749
This is a National Geographic map of oil infrastructure
in the Gulf moving out to about 150 miles.

00:06:08.749 --> 00:06:10.900
This is physical infrastructure in the ocean.

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:14.530
When you look out in the ocean off the coast
of California, you see almost none of this

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:18.169
physical infrastructure because thereís moratorium
in oil drilling.

00:06:18.169 --> 00:06:22.770
The Gulf of Mexico is a very different story
and the waters of a lot of countries around

00:06:22.770 --> 00:06:26.710
the world is a very different story in terms
of oil exploration This is changing the way

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:27.930
we think of the oceans.

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:32.189
Weíre thinking about it as a space; a space
to be used and a space to be managed in a

00:06:32.189 --> 00:06:36.319
way that we only thought of possible on land
before.

00:06:36.319 --> 00:06:41.550
In some places, the rule of law for the oceans
is also incredibly challenging; such that

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:46.629
people are using dynamite still to fish or
to collect coastal aggregate materials for

00:06:46.629 --> 00:06:47.629
construction.

00:06:47.629 --> 00:06:51.279
This is a photo I took in the Marshall Islands,
where I lived for four years working for their

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:56.509
government, where theyíre still using reef
resources for mining materials because there

00:06:56.509 --> 00:06:59.400
is no other resources for construction materials.

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:06.249
So the physical use of near shore reefs is
another significant challenge we face.

00:07:06.249 --> 00:07:10.110
And then finally, as we all have heard from
many different angles, but we cannot mention

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:15.029
the oceans without describing the situation
of climate change and its impact to the oceans.

00:07:15.029 --> 00:07:20.500
This is a reef in Aceh in Indonesia a year
ago prior to, a year and a half ago, prior

00:07:20.500 --> 00:07:25.379
to the bleaching event that bleached out 100
percent of certain species of corals, in a

00:07:25.379 --> 00:07:26.939
site where we worked.

00:07:26.939 --> 00:07:32.169
So the white is what happens to corals when
all their symbiotic algae is expelled and

00:07:32.169 --> 00:07:37.460
if the temperatures do not decrease after
a few weeks, the corals die, and thatís what

00:07:37.460 --> 00:07:38.789
has happened in Indonesia.

00:07:38.789 --> 00:07:43.039
It happened in a lot of places around the
world when temperatures were elevated.

00:07:43.039 --> 00:07:51.289
So, like many ecosystems, the global impact
on climate change is also a considerable challenge.

00:07:51.289 --> 00:07:55.990
This all being said, there is significant
hope in the oceans like there has not been

00:07:55.990 --> 00:07:57.090
before.

00:07:57.090 --> 00:08:01.819
There is a changing mindset in people and
in countries around the world to try to find

00:08:01.819 --> 00:08:07.229
a way to better protect, better manage your
fisheries, expand protected areas out in the

00:08:07.229 --> 00:08:12.249
oceans, ensure smart growth as opposed to
unregulated growth of extractive industries

00:08:12.249 --> 00:08:16.969
and invest significantly more into scientific
research and understanding of the vast waters

00:08:16.969 --> 00:08:17.999
of our planet.

00:08:17.999 --> 00:08:23.509
Weíve invested a lot of money and time in
understanding domestic waters of the US.

00:08:23.509 --> 00:08:27.110
And now a lot of that is changing to expand
throughout the world.

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:32.529
Just to point you out a bit of where we focus
is that thereís three centers of marine biodiversity

00:08:32.529 --> 00:08:34.030
in the planet.

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:37.810
Basically the western edge of ocean basins,
so the western edge of the Atlantic is the

00:08:37.810 --> 00:08:41.540
Caribbean, western edge of the Indian, the
western Indian Ocean and the western edge

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:45.400
of the Pacific Ocean, these are the hearts
of marine biodiversity.

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:50.270
Areas that are generally very nutrient poor
but have vast coral reef resources.

00:08:50.270 --> 00:08:56.130
So these places are, in a planet that is covered
72 percent by ocean, some of the most critical

00:08:56.130 --> 00:09:00.930
places to work to expand in protected areas
and improving fisheries.

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:06.600
There are also some places, again, along the
coast, where the greatest amount of productivity

00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:10.360
is happening on the oceans, where 90 percent
of marine life is existing in the coastal

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:13.870
zone and you have huge aggregations of coastal
wildlife.

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:17.610
The Congo basin coast in Central Africa has
the worldís largest population of Leatherback

00:09:17.610 --> 00:09:18.610
Sea Turtles.

00:09:18.610 --> 00:09:22.710
For folks that have seen Leatherbacks, theyíre
talking 9 feet long, these creatures that

00:09:22.710 --> 00:09:27.580
are extremely vulnerable, the last, the largest
population in the planet lives here and is

00:09:27.580 --> 00:09:29.030
doing very well.

00:09:29.030 --> 00:09:32.920
The Bay of Bengal has the worldís largest
population of Irrawaddy river dolphins and

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:36.010
coastal cetaceans
. But the government of Bangladesh, one of

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:39.830
the poorest countries on the planet, just
put in a protected area to protect a whole

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:44.570
slew of the population of river dolphins that
is bigger by a factor of ten than any other

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:47.400
population on the planet.

00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:52.110
And in the Arctic, between Alaska and Russia,
which is experiencing incredible impacts from

00:09:52.110 --> 00:09:56.550
climate change and receding of ice, there
was an effort to continue to protect walrus

00:09:56.550 --> 00:10:00.880
